data.chText: 主要的；首要的；基本的
data.enText: main; most important; basic

data.chText: 我最关心的是保护自己的财产。
data.enText: My prime concern is to protect my property.

data.chText: 获胜不是这项体育运动的主要目的。
data.enText: Winning is not the prime objective in this sport.

data.chText: 保护环境是最重要的。
data.enText: The care of the environment is of prime importance.

data.chText: 他是该案中警方的主要怀疑对象。
data.enText: He's the police's prime suspect in this case.

data.chText: 优质的；上乘的；优异的
data.enText: of the best quality; excellent

data.chText: 上等的牛肉（块）
data.enText: prime (cuts of) beef

data.chText: 这家商店位于商业中心一个非常理想的位置。
data.enText: The store has a prime position in the mall.

data.chText: 典型的；有代表性的
data.enText: a prime example of sth is one that is typical of it

data.chText: 这座大楼是20世纪60年代的典型建筑。
data.enText: The building is a prime example of 1960s architecture.

data.chText: 最可能的；首选的；最适宜的
data.enText: most likely to be chosen for sth; most suitable

data.chText: 这座孤零零的房子是盗贼的首选目标。
data.enText: The house is isolated and a prime target for burglars.

data.chText: 他是最有望获得晋升的人选。
data.enText: He's a prime candidate for promotion.

data.chText: 盛年；年富力强的时期；鼎盛时期
data.enText: the time in your life when you are strongest or most successful

data.chText: 正当妙龄的女郎
data.enText: a young woman in her prime

data.chText: 他还不满30岁，正是英姿勃发的年华。
data.enText: He was barely 30 and in the prime of (his) life .

data.chText: 这些花的鼎盛花期早过了。
data.enText: These flowers are long past their prime .

data.chText: 事先指点；使（某人）做好准备
data.enText: to prepare sb for a situation so that they know what to do, especially by giving them special information

data.chText: 他们事先得到了高人指点。
data.enText: They had been primed with good advice.

data.chText: 她已胸有成竹、跃跃欲试了。
data.enText: She was ready and primed for action.

data.chText: 他已经知会他的朋友，尽量少向记者透露消息。

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+带to的不定式

data.enText: He had primed his friends to give the journalists as little information as possible.

data.chText: 把（事物）准备好
data.enText: to make sth ready for use or action

data.chText: 炸弹已准备好，可随时引爆。
data.enText: The bomb was primed, ready to explode.

data.chText: 在（金属、木材等上）打底漆
data.enText: to prepare wood, metal, etc. for painting by covering it with a special paint that helps the next layer of paint to stay on
prime the pump

data.chText: 投资以振兴（新的或不景气的企业或行业）
data.enText: to encourage the growth of a new or weak business or industry by putting money into it

data.text: main ♦ major ♦ key ♦ central ♦ principal ♦ chief ♦ prime

data.chText: 以上各词均用以形容主要的、最重要的人或事物。
data.enText: These words all describe sb/sth that is the largest or most important of its kind.
main

data.chText: 指主要的、最重要的：
data.enText: [only before noun] largest or most important

data.chText: 过大马路时小心点。
data.enText: Be careful crossing the main road.

data.chText: 最重要的是要保持冷静。
data.enText: The main thing is to remain calm.
major

data.chText: 指主要的、重要的、大的：
data.enText: [usually before noun] very large or important

data.chText: 他在建立这个系统的过程中扮演了主要的角色。
data.enText: He played a major role in setting up the system.

data.chText: major最常用于不定冠词a之后，与单数名词连用；或不用冠词，与复数名词连用。major与the或my/your/his/her/our/their连用时意为最主要的、最重要的：
data.enText: Major is most often used after a with a singular noun, or no article with a plural noun. When it is used with the or my/your/his/her/our/their it means ‘the largest or most important’.

data.chText: 在这里我们最关心的是解决贫穷问题。
data.enText: Our major concern here is combatting poverty.

data.chText: 在该含义中major只用以指人的想法或担忧，而非物质的东西，且较main正式：
data.enText: In this meaning it is only used to talk about ideas or worries that people have, not physical things, and it is also more formal than main .
Be careful crossing the major road.
The major thing is to remain calm.
key

data.chText: 指最重要的、主要的、关键的：
data.enText: [usually before noun] most important; essential

data.chText: 他是这场运动的关键人物。
data.enText: He was a key figure in the campaign.

data.chText: key最常用于商务和政治语境，可用以指想法或某人在某情势下起的作用，而非物质的东西。key较major稍非正式，用于名词加连系动词后尤其如此：
data.enText: Key is used most frequently in business and political contexts. It can be used to talk about ideas, or the part that sb plays in a situation, but not physical things. It is slightly more informal than major , especially when used after a noun and linking verb.

data.chText: 在这个时候速度是关键。
data.enText: Speed is key at this point.
central

data.chText: 指最重要的、首要的、主要的：
data.enText: ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 最重要的问题是种族主义泛滥。
data.enText: The central issue is that of widespread racism.

data.chText: central与key用法相似，但更正式，最常用于be central to短语中。
data.enText: Central is used in a similar way to key , but is more formal. It is most frequently used in the phrase sth is central to sth else .
principal

data.chText: 指最重要的、主要的：
data.enText: [only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 跳过它的主要原因是时间不足。
data.enText: The principal reason for this omission is lack of time.

data.chText: principal主要用于陈述无可争辩的事实。表明意见或说服别人相信你所见到的事实，较常用key或central：
data.enText: Principal is mostly used for statements of fact about which there can be no argument. To state an opinion, or to try to persuade sb of the facts as you see them, it is more usual to use key or central .

data.chText: 这里的关键问题是…
data.enText: The key/central issue here is …
chief

data.chText: 指最重要的、首要的、主要的：
data.enText: [only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important

data.chText: 失业是贫穷的主要原因。
data.enText: Unemployment was the chief cause of poverty.
prime

data.chText: 指主要的、首要的：
data.enText: [only before noun] ( rather formal ) most important; to be considered first

data.chText: 我最关心的是保护自己的财产。
data.enText: My prime concern is to protect my property.

value.def: You use prime to describe something that is most important in a situation.

example.ex: Political stability, meanwhile, will be a prime concern...
example.tran: 同时，政治稳定性将放在首位。

example.ex: It could be a prime target for guerrilla attack...
example.tran: 这可能是游击队进攻的主要目标。

example.ex: The police will see me as the prime suspect!
example.tran: 警方会把我当作头号嫌疑人！

example.ex: Prime candidate to take over his job is Margaret Ramsay.
example.tran: 接替他工作的首要人选是玛格丽特·拉姆齐。

value.tran: 主要的；首要的；最为重要的

value.def: You use prime to describe something that is of the best possible quality.

example.ex: It was one of the City's prime sites, near the Stock Exchange.
example.tran: 这是伦敦最好的地段之一，离证券交易所很近。

value.tran: 优质的；一流的；上等的；最好的

value.def: You use prime to describe an example of a particular kind of thing that is absolutely typical.

example.ex: The prime example is Macy's, once the undisputed king of California retailers.
example.tran: 最典型的例子是梅西百货，它曾经是加利福尼亚无可争辩的零售巨头。

value.tran: 最典型的；最有代表性的

value.def: If someone or something is in their prime, they are at the stage in their existence when they are at their strongest, most active, or most successful.

example.ex: Maybe I'm just coming into my prime now...
example.tran: 也许我现在正要步入事业辉煌期。

example.ex: She was in her intellectual prime...
example.tran: 在智力上，她正处于壮年。

example.ex: We've had a series of athletes trying to come back well past their prime.
example.tran: 我们有些早已过了黄金期的运动员仍然想东山再起。

example.ex: ...young persons in the prime of life.

value.tran: 全盛时期；最活跃时期；最成功时期

value.def: If you prime someone to do something, you prepare them to do it, for example by giving them information about it beforehand.

example.ex: Claire wished she'd primed Sarah beforehand...
example.tran: 克莱尔真希望她事先指点过萨拉。

example.ex: Arnold primed her for her duties...
example.tran: 阿诺德事先让她熟悉了自己的任务。

example.ex: The press corps was primed to leap to the defense of the fired officials.
example.tran: 记者团获知信息后，立即声援被解雇官员。

value.def: If someone primes a bomb or a gun, they prepare it so that it is ready to explode or fire.

example.ex: He was priming the bomb to go off in an hour's time...
example.tran: 他正在装炸弹，设定为在一个小时之内爆炸。

example.ex: Tom keeps a primed 10-foot shotgun in his office.
example.tran: 汤姆在办公室放了一支装了子弹的10英尺长的猎枪。
